<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900730-0062</DOCNO><DOCID>900730-0062.</DOCID><HL>   Rep. Gonzalez Plans Probe   On Treasury Use of Funds</HL><DATE>07/30/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   LATAM</CO><IN>BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)</IN><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- House Banking Committee Chairman Henry B.Gonzalez announced plans to investigate the TreasuryDepartment's use of government funds for intervening incurrency markets and for funding its Third World debt plan.   The Texas Democrat said he plans a series of hearingsstarting Aug. 14.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Gonzalez, in a statement, said, &quot;The American peoplehave the right to know how their hard-earned tax dollars arebeing spent . . . yet the Treasury and the Federal Reserveapparently believe that Congress and the American taxpayer donot have the right to question certain aspects of theirinternational activities.&quot; He said this &quot;intolerable attitudetoward accountability to the American people cannot bejustified.&quot;   At issue is the $25 billion exchange stabilization fundthat the Treasury uses to intervene in foreign currencymarkets. Mr. Gonzalez called it a &quot;slush fund that lackspublic scrutiny.&quot; He said his committee will investigatewhether the Treasury Department should be banned frommanipulating the foreign-exchange value of the dollar andthat power be given exclusively to the Federal Reserve.   In addition, Mr. Gonzalez plans to look into a Treasuryagreement to sell zero-coupon bonds to Mexico at below-marketprices, in effect subsidizing the bonds with taxpayers'money.</TEXT></DOC>